		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Axial Age</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub">&nbsp;&nbsp;(Redirected from <a href="/w/index.php?title=Axial_age&amp;redirect=no" title="Axial age">Axial age</a>)</div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">German</a> <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">philosopher</a> <a href="/wiki/Karl_Jaspers" title="Karl Jaspers">Karl Jaspers</a> coined the term the <b>axial age</b><sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since October 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup> (<a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">Ger.</a> <i>Achsenzeit</i>, "axistime") to describe the period from <a href="/wiki/8th_century_BC" title="8th century BC">800 BC</a> to <a href="/wiki/2nd_century_BC" title="2nd century BC">200 BC</a>, during which, according to Jaspers, similarly revolutionary thinking appeared in <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>, <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Occident" title="Occident" class="mw-redirect">Occident</a>. The period is also sometimes referred to as the <b>axis age</b>.<sup id="cite_ref-Mickolichek_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mickolichek-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Jaspers, in his <i>Vom Ursprung und Ziel der Geschichte</i> (<i>The Origin and Goal of History</i>), identified a number of key axial age thinkers as having had a profound influence on future philosophy and religion, and identified characteristics common to each area from which those thinkers emerged. Jaspers saw in these developments in <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religion</a> and <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a> a striking parallel without any obvious direct transmission of ideas from one region to the other, having found no recorded proof of any extensive intercommunication between <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">Ancient Greece</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Middle_East" title="Middle East">Middle East</a>, India, and China. Jaspers held up this age as unique, and one to which the rest of the <a href="/wiki/History_of_ideas" title="History of ideas">history of human thought</a> might be compared. Jaspers' approach to the culture of the middle of the first millennium BC has been adopted by other scholars and academics, and has become a point of discussion in the <a href="/wiki/History_of_religion" title="History of religion" class="mw-redirect">history of religion</a>.</p>
